{"0": "Getting less sleep has become a bad habit for most American kids.", "1": "According to a new survey by the National Sleep Foundation, 51% of kids aged 10 to 18 go to bed at 10 pm or later on school nights, even though they have to get up early.", "2": "Last year the Foundation reported that nearly 60% of 7- to 12-year-olds said they felt tired during the day, and 15% said they had fallen asleep at school.", "3": "How much sleep you need depends a lot on your age.", "4": "Babies need a lot of rest: most of them sleep about 18 hours a day!", "5": "Adults need about eight hours.", "6": "For most school-age children, ten hours is ideal.", "7": "But the new National Sleep Foundation survey found that 35% of 10- to 12-year-olds get only seven or eight hours.", "8": "And guess what almost half of the surveyed kids said they do before bedtime?", "9": "Watch TV.", "10": "\"More children are going to bed with TVs on, and there are more opportunities to stay awake, with more homework, the Internet and the phone,\" says Dr. Mary Carskadon, a sleep researcher at Brown University Medical School.", "11": "She says these activities at bedtime can get kids all excited and make it hard for them to calm down and sleep.", "12": "Other experts say part of the problem is chemical.", "13": "Changing levels of body chemicals called hormones not only make teenagers' bodies develop adult characteristics, but also make it hard for teenagers to fall asleep before 11 pm.", "14": "Because sleepiness is such a problem for teenagers, some school districts have decided to start high school classes later than they used to.", "15": "Three years ago, schools in Edina, Minnesota, changed the start time from 7:25 am to 8:30 am.", "16": "Students, parents and teachers are pleased with the results."}